A constitution is DIFFERENT from CLAUDE.md:
- CLAUDE.md = how to work in this repo (commands, conventions, session ritual)
- CONSTITUTION.md = the non-negotiable invariants this project will not violate

Invariants are the rules an agent must re-validate against at plan time,
implement time, and review time. They're the drift anchor. Each invariant is
a hard constraint with a rationale + a verification method.

Questions to ask (infer from codebase first where possible, then confirm):

1. ARCHITECTURAL INVARIANTS — "What structural rules must NEVER be broken?
   (e.g. 'all DB writes go through the reconcile layer', 'no business logic
   in controllers', 'the CLI and MCP server are both generated from one
   contract'.) I'll infer candidates from the code; you confirm + add."
   Infer from: directory structure, existing abstractions, any ARCHITECTURE.md.

2. QUALITY BARS — "What's the non-negotiable quality gate? (e.g. 'typecheck
   must pass before commit', 'every new feature needs a test', 'no PR merges
   with failing CI'.)"
   Infer from: CI config, test setup, package.json scripts.

3. SECURITY RULES — "What security invariants are absolute? (e.g. 'no secrets
   in markdown or committed files', 'all auth checks server-side', 'untrusted
   input never reaches the shell'.)"
   Infer from: .gitignore patterns, any auth/secrets handling in code.

4. DATA RULES — "What data discipline is mandatory? (e.g. 'schema changes
   require a migration', 'no destructive ops without a backup', 'PII is
   encrypted at rest'.)"
   Infer from: migration dirs, schema files, ORM usage.

5. PROCESS RULES — "How do changes land? (e.g. 'feature branches only, no
   direct main commits', 'every change gets a CHANGELOG entry', 'VERSION
   bumps in N files at once'.)"
   Infer from: branch protection, CONTRIBUTING.md, release scripts.

